deck_excerpt: For When the OCG Cyberse Support is Imported
deck_description:
This deck took so long to make, but I think the end product was well worth it. It’s been 6 months of testing and trying, but in the end what I have is far better than what I started with, and I am truly pleased (and I think you will be too). I bring you the optimal way, in my opinion, to play:

Code Talkers 

Disclaimers: This deck uses (and relies heavily on) certain OCG cards that have not yet come to the TCG. This deck also doesn’t take into consideration price; I was simply attempting to create the best possible deck I could, not one on a budget.  

Section 1: Why Play Code Talker?

Code Talker isn’t really known for being the strongest Cyberse deck out there; that honor is awarded to Salamangreats. Code Talkers are also overshadowed in the TCG (and OCG) by @Ignister, a good archetype in its own right. So why would you play Code Talker over these “better” archetypes? Well, Code Talker is a mix of both Salamangreat and @ignister, especially the way that I would tend to play it. Especially with Decode Talker Heatsoul, Code Talker can play a really strong control option with just contemporary hand traps and its omni-negate Cynet Conflict. Typically, the ending setup is Heatsoul w/ Conflict or an Xyz with 2 or more hand traps. The best I’ve come across is Heatsoul + Conflict + Xyz + 3 hand traps, meaning a total of 5 possible negates and either an out for your opponent’s monster effects or GY effects. That, and because of the plethora of hand traps and Cyberse swarm power, Code Talker can even OTK effectively by preventing your opponent’s end board and demolishing them with Accesscode Talker + Firewall Dragon. The power of this deck compares with many others; I’ve tested it against meta decks (although I don’t know how effective they were piloted or if they simply got a stroke of bad luck, so that isn’t necessarily an irrefutable measure) and I’ve come out on top a lot, so obviously there’s potential here when the OCG cards come out.    So now that I have convinced you (or at least got you reading this far), how do you play Code Talkers effectively? Well...  

Section 2: Strategy + Basic Power Cards

  Going first, your primary goal is this: Decode Talker Heatsoul with as many negates/hand traps as possible. Note that there are a variety of ways to do this; in fact, 10 cards in the deck have the capability of netting you a Heatsoul by themselves: Lady Debug, Cyberse Gadget, Dotscaper and Cynet Mining. To get Cynet Conflict (your go-to omni-negate), you can either dry draw it or use Micro Coder. If you draw into Parallel eXceed, you can get either Number 41: Bagooska or Abyss Dweller for a strong end board. Your goal is to then survive through your opponent’s turn with minimal damage and return strong with Accesscode Talker and Firewall Dragon to wipe the field and/or Heatsoul/Transcode Talker for attack gain. So how do you do all of this?   For first turn, if you draw into either Lady Debug, Cyberse Gadget, Dotscaper or Cynet Mining, you have a free Heatsoul (second turn all of these can get you a free Accesscode). Here’s how: Lady Debug: Normal Summon, add Code Generator. Debug + Generator (in hand) into Code Talker, mill Dotscaper off Generator’s eff, Special Summoning it. Code Talker and Dot into Heatsoul. Cyberse Gadget: Normal Summon. Link into Link Disciple, summoning Token. Token + Disciple into Splash Mage. Mage summon Gadget, link into Heatsoul. Dotscaper: Normal Summon. Link into Link Disciple/Salamangreat Almiraj, summoning Dotscaper from grave by its own eff. Link Disciple/Almiraj + Dot into Splash Mage. Mage summon Dot, link into Heatsoul. Cynet Mining: Search any of the above. Note that if you’re worried about Nibiru, search Lady Debug. (To get Accesscode, simply link into Transcode Talker instead of Heatsoul, summoning a Link from grave and then linking into Accesscode.)   If you don’t run into any of these, no worries! If you have 2 low-level extenders or a low-level hand trap and an extender, you can still get Heatsoul! Link the extenders into Disciple and the hand traps into Almiraj, and you’re good to go from there.   Third turn (and also going second) doesn’t have a specific combo, it’s just getting as much ATK as you can to finish them off.   Now it’s time to go into why I chose some cards over others:  

Section 3: Why Do You Have This One Instead of That One?

There were a few things that I switched out and plain deleted over the course of optimizing this deck. One thing that any Code Talker player will say when they see this deck is: why is there no Cynet Codec? And my response is: Codec is strong, sure, but there’s nothing that it can do to make the deck more effective. This deck can already get an Accesscode off of 1 card in hand; not to mention there’s plenty of extenders in this deck. Therefore, the extra power provided by Codec isn’t necessary.    Another thing people may notice: why do I have Link Spider? Two reasons: Nibiru token and Gadget token. If you need more of an explanation, you haven’t played Yu-Gi-Oh! long enough.   Something else: why do I have 3 of Parallel eXceed? Because I really want to see it, and it will never be a brick because of how much you Link Summon. There’s really no reason not to.   Red Reboot is in there because not only is it a good hand trap, but it also can negate Infinite Impermanence, which can absolutely destroy this deck if you only have Debug (which is uncommon but can happen). You can definitely replace this with another hand trap or with Imperial Order.   All hand traps can be replaced in the main with others depending on the meta, with two exceptions: Ash Blossom and Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay. Ash for obvious reasons, Phantazmay because that hand fix ability and the protection can absolutely save this deck. I also wouldn’t get rid of Effect Veiler personally, but that’s simply my personal opinion.   Forbidden Droplet is there instead of Dark Ruler No More because when you have OTK potential, it’s stupid to throw it out the window by having your opponent take 0 damage.   If you have any questions for why any of the cards are what they are, just comment on this and I’ll get back to you as soon as I can.  

Section 4: General Comments

If you have Cynet Conflict set, make sure not to activate Lancea until you’ve used it, because Lancea interferes with the second part of it. I believe that you can still negate with Conflict, but it just won’t banish and lock your opponent from using another card of the same name, but I’m not certain.   Proxy Horse and Flame Bufferlo are useful when you have multiple starters in hand. Horse is also the alternative grave send off of Generator.    There are 12 starters (3 Lady Debug, 3 Cyberse Gadget, 3 Cynet Mining, 1 Dotscaper, 1 Proxy Horse, 1 Flame Bufferlo), 16 hand traps (3 Ash, 3 Veiler, 3 Phantazmay, 2 Lancea, 2 Ghost Belle, 1 Nibiru, 1 Imperm, 1 Reboot), 11 extenders (3 Micro Coder, 3 Parallel eXceed, 2 Code Generator, 2 Code Exporter, 1 Code Radiator) and 3 negates (3 Cynet Conflict). That’s 42 cards with no draw cards, so you may think that this deck wouldn’t be the best. But it’s still very consistant, with about an 80% chance of seeing a starter, and a higher chance if you include workable hands with 2 extenders or a summonable hand trap and an extender.    You can probably main 3 Nibiru, since your only monster on the field usually is Heatsoul going first. I don’t like that option, as it messes with your turn 3 strat, but it’ll work and may be more effective in the long run.   This deck is hit hardest by Psy-framegear Gamma (on Debug or Splash), Nibiru (although it can possibly work through it with enough extenders) and any negates with a destruction/banish clause. Cannot play through Summon Limit, There Can Only Be One or Gozen Match unless you draw a whole ton of Code extenders. Anything that negates on-field effects and/or graveyard effects destroys any potential for getting a win without spell/trap removal.    Kaijus and other side-deck monsters such as Prankratops and Alpha, King of Beasts don’t really work with this deck as they mess with Transcode’s requirement. Feel free to try it, but I can say that it probably won’t work.   As always, feel free to do what you like with it. Any questions can go in the comments, as well as any suggestions for making it better. Thanks!

deck_excerpt: I like using this deck because Adamancipators are really consistent at getting out level 6 and level 8 synchro's, and 1 day I wanted to find out an ea
deck_description: For this combo, the best hand you can probably get is Adamancipator Researcher, Any level 4 Rock type monster, and an Adamancipator Signs.  For the start of the combo, you want to summon 1 level 4 rock monster in your hand, special summon Adamancipator Researcher and then use her effect to excavate 5, with that effect you want to summon another level 4 rock monster (If you manage to excavate Prank-Kids Rocksies you can also go for The Prank-kids combo in the deck and then continue). Then you want to XYZ summon into your rank 4 Gallant Granite, use it's effect to add a Adamancipator Seeker to hand from deck, you then want to special summon Adamancipator Seeker from your hand and then using its effect to excavate 5 cards special summoning a level 4 rock monster. With the level 4 rock monster and your Adamancipator seeker you want to Synchro summon into Adamancipator Risen - Raptite, you want to excavate 5 cards again, based on what you excavate you can go to the appropriate steps:  Adamancipator Analyzer/ Doki Doki: If you excavate Adamancipator Analyzer or Doki Doki you can special summon 1 of them then either use Doki Doki effect to discard 1 level 4 rock monster so you can special summon Adamancipator Analyzer, or just summon it with Adamancipator Risen - Raptite, then you want to excavate 5 cards summoning a level 4 rock type monster. With that you want to then use Adamancipator Researcher and Adamancipator Risen - Raptite, going into Adamancipator Risen - Dragite. Then using Adamancipator Analyzer, and your remaining level 4 rock type monster to go into your Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend, after that you would activate Adamancipator Signs bringing back either Adamancipator Researcher or Adamancipator Seeker, then linking into Crystron Halqifibrax with Gallant Granite (or Prank-Kids Doodle-doo if you did the Prank-kids combo with Prank-Kids Rocksies) with Crystron Halqifibrax you want to summon your Plaguespreader Zombie from either your hand or deck, after that going into Baroness de Fleur with Adamancipator Dragite and Plaguespreader Zombie. After that using Plaguespreader Zombie effect to revive self.  A level 4 rock type monster: If you excavate a level 4 rock type monster, you want to then Link Summon into Crystron Halqifibrax with that level 4 rock monster and Adamancipator Researcher, with Crystron Halqifibrax effect to summon Plaguespreader Zombie from hand or deck to field, then Synchro summoning into Scarlight Red Dragon Archfiend with Adamancipator Risen - Raptite and Plaguespreader Zombie, After that using Plaguespreader effect in your GY to revive itself.  After you use one of those 2 effects you want to then pass your turn. on the start of your opponent's main phase you want to use Crystron Halqifibrax effect to summon Formula Synchron. The next move your opponent makes you want to use Formula Synchron's effect, using Scarlight Red Dragon Plaguespreader Zombie, and Formula Synchron into Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity.     While this Combo does limit you to only 1 or not even any negates I would say it is okay as with Hot Red Dragon Archfiend King Calamity you cannot activate effects in the first place. Even though this combo would seem pretty consistent, it is more of a Fun deck because it easily dies to Dark Ruler no More(at the same time almost every deck dies to DRNM). you can get your King Calamity Tributed with either Sphere Mode or Lava Golem but it is a lingering effect therefore your opponent cannot use his/her effects still.  Hope you enjoy the deck!

A couple of notes on the deck....... I've found that you only need water extenders after your initial normal summon, along with the rank 4 monsters being bonkers better than linking off into a link 4. Because of that, I took out sleepy maiden for more level 4 extenders.     I'm also not playing Reef...... but I want to. I'm not sure what the best card in the extra is though. Kragen spawn may be a really good card, but idk. It allows me to have more follow up if my board is broken.     I'm going to experiment with maiden in the future (probably), along with the other new shark card that comes back from the grave. Crystal shark is the perfect discard for the new link 3, so that may go in over a sea nettle, but it also has the potential of bricking a hand if you don't have another level 5 or 4 that can be left over at the end of your combo.     Lastly, I've placed wave at 1. 3 is too much, but I can't tell if I want to play 2 when it is so easy to search.     LMK what y'all think of the deck. I'd be happy to have any feedback!

deck_name: Magnet Warrior Deck - Post BACH (OCG Release 2021)
deck_description: Introduction When Block Dragon was banned in September 2020 (TCG) after the release of Adamancipators in the Secret Slayers expansion, Rock Decks suffered tremendously from the loss of one of their most prominent staples (you know, that wasn't Gorgonic Guardian). (This was due to its last effect, which allowed you to add all of the Adamancipator Tuners, which I agree, is pretty broken.) With the loss of such a powerful defensive utility, Rock Decks were forced to take a new approach that they have been quite good at recently: Beatdown. Best Beatdown Rock Archetypes as of 2021 First of, one of the most significant Rock Archetypes ever would have to be Adamancipators. The Tuners synergize very well with all Rocks, and they can quickly make heavy Synchros such as Adamancipator Risen - Dragite, Borreload Savage Dragon, and Crystal Wing Synchro Dragon (mainly the first two, as you have to work a bit for Crystal Wing). (Not to mention it can also function as a Stun Deck if it is integrated with Koa'ki Meiru.) Another significant Rock Archetype that has recently been introduced would be the Fossil Archetype, which is the literal embodiment of beatdown. Being able to Fusion Summon with materials from either Graveyard is excellent (not to mention the rewards you get for using materials from your opponent's Graveyard), and the ace Fusion Monsters are all Battle Phase oriented (the best one being Fossil Dragon Skullgios). The last Rock Archetype that has had some considerable support in 2021 would be Magnet Warriors. Although Magnet Warriors are lacking in removal options, they specialize in mediocre swarming (literally every card in the archetype, except the original 3 Normal Monsters, has an effect to Special Summon something), and while the archetype itself does not explicitly reward the player for getting 5 Level 4 monsters on your opponent's turn, it does open up itself as an engine for other Rock Decks (mainly the aforementioned two). And with the release of the new Epsilon The Magnet Warrior (OCG), Magnet Warriors are a very strong going first Archetype due to their somewhat untouchability during the opponent's turn, even without access to Block Dragon. So... we should start talking about this Deck then This is an Adamancipator/Fossil Beatdown Deck that uses Magnet Warriors as its main engine (wow, how original) for Synchro material and Fusion Material. The Deck is somewhat balanced in terms of its in-game adaptability, 1) being able to open a strong going first board with Magnet Warriors that gives you a full field and Graveyard set-up on your next turn or 2) being able to establish stable footing for itself going second with Adamancipators and Fossils (since your opponent's Graveyard is most likely already established). Do note that the Deck is very swarm heavy, and because of this it is unfortunately very dependent on careful zone usage and placement (the Link era still leaves its tracks in the mud lol). Win Condition The best possible field that could be established with this Deck would be having Adamancipator Risen - Dragite as your main disruptor, Fossil Machine Skull Convoy (to get through walls of big monsters and get that residual damage) or Fossil Dragon Skullgios (it's essentially Blue-Eyes Chaos Max just without the protection), a Gorgonic Guardian or two (I shouldn't have to explain this), and Berserkion the Electromagna Warrior since it punishes your opponent if they happen to bomb your entire field all at once. (It wouldn't hurt to have a Magnetic Field out too, but it's a shame it's not SEARCHABLE.) However, if you want to tie up a match quickly, a funny way to game end is with Fossil Dragon Skullgios and Number 60: Dugares the Timeless (but that's only if you want to be extra cheeky).

deck_excerpt: Infinity? Toad? Trish? Halq? WEEEEE HAVE IT ALLLLLLLLLLLL!
deck_description: Trying to take full advantage of pendulum summoning, as nerfed as it is, to power out powerful stuff. The various synchros can be summoned with Halq or with Deskbot 001, Halq goes into Shooting Riser, whose level is easily manipulatable since we have main deck monsters from 3-5, letting SRD be anywhere from Lv 2-4 for synchro summoning. The Symphonic Warriors and Ice Knights give us extra normal summons so we can save our pendulum summon for reusing our pedulums after they get set to the extra deck, and Hamster and Pendulum XYZ let us get a little extra value out of being a pendulum deck.  Brachion makes us want to go second, and our boss monsters either shred boards (Trish, Trish-Zero) or are powerful negates (Toad, Borrelload Savage,) or both (Infinity, Fleur), so we canuse that and our hand traps to fight through an established board.  Just like in 2017, Dinomists are a cheap, mediocre engine that gets to play a wide variety of powerful but expensive boss monsters.

We all know Salamangreat in this Format but... "Salamangreat"  is an archetype of FIRE Cyberse monsters The "Salmangreat" monsters have various effects related to battle and GY recursion. A common theme among many of their monsters is they work best when with another monster of the same name. The most simple and powerful example is "Salamangreat Gazelle" who sends any "Salamangreat" card from the Deck to the GY, and can also Special Summon itself from the hand if a "Salamangreat" monster is sent to the GY. Many of the archetype's effects also involve shuffling cards from the GY into the Deck, revival and discarding cards, so manipulation of the GY successfully gives the Deck a lot of potential. A key part of the Deck's combos is "Salamangreat Sanctuary", which allows the player to use a "Salamangreat" with the same name as a monster being Link Summoned as the entire material. As with the lesser monsters, the boss monsters get stronger when Summoned using a monster with the same name, making "Sanctuary" the quickest and easiest way to open up the full potential of the Deck's Link monsters. It can be searched by "Salamangreat Balelynx" to increase consistency, which makes generic Cyberse monsters like "Lady Debug" and "Flame Bufferlo" useful to start combos off. The main win condition in some builds is to set up a "Salamangreat Violet Chimera" Summoned using another copy of itself, which basically guarantees an OTK if all its effects resolve. The other Extra Deck monsters can be used to support this strategy, or for supporting the Deck's recursion/battle effects. In more conventional builds, "Violet Chimera" can simply used with "Fusion of Fire" and "Super Polymerization" to break up Link-focused boards, particularly deadly in mirror matches. The Deck's rarely used Ritual Monster "Salamangreat Emerald Eagle" provides a finisher/alternate attacker that can clear all the opponent's Special Summoned monsters if Ritual Summoned using an "Emerald Eagle" the player controls, and can sacrifice unneeded Link Monsters to get over tough monsters while inflicting heavy Burn damage. As any modern Deck must, the Spell/Trap lineup of the Deck also has a heavy control element. "Salamangreat Roar" is a powerful Counter Trap Card that can negate any monster effect or Spell/Trap card while you control a "Salamangreat" Link Monster, that can Set itself from the GY when a "Salamangreat" is self-Link Summoned at the cost of banishing itself when it leaves the field. It can also be recovered by "Salamangreat Sunlight Wolf", who can also play a key role in grabbing "Fusion of Fire" or other key Spell/Trap cards from the GY, especially ones sent by "Gazelle". Many of these like "Will of the Salamangreat", "Salamangreat Circle" and "Salamangreat Rage" get stronger when a self-Summoned Salamangreat Link Monster is present, so maintaining and protecting a powerful monster like "Salamangreat Heatleo" can reap many rewards, even over a relatively short Duel. "Sunlight Wolf" can also recover FIRE monsters from the GY, particularly useful with the staple handtrap "Ash Blossom & Joyous Spring". These attributes of repeated recursion allow the Deck to get a lot of value from playing many on-theme 1-ofs, as they will nearly always be accessible when needed. Finally, a key step in setting up these plays is "Salamangreat Miragestallio", a generic Rank 3 that can Summon any "Salamangreat" from the Deck and bounce opposing cards on being used as Link Material (Traditional only). An alternative to "Miragestallio" is "Dante, Traveler of the Burning Abyss". As such the Deck works well with generic Rank 3 engines such as "Speedroids", "Danger!" and "Predaplants".

Welcome to Area 51! Where the goal is to corrupt your monsters and turn them into mindless drones! We come in peace... or do we...   The idea behind this deck is to flood the field with "A" counters by using "A" Cell Recombination Device so you can take over your opponents' monsters and use them as fodder for your summons. By sending an Alien monster from the deck to the GY you can place counters on an opponent's monster up to the level of the sent monster. The main strategy is to quickly summon Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll and use both of his effects.   In order to do that, we need to flood the field with Aliens. In order to do that, we need to bring out Alien Shocktrooper M-Frame. The effect of M-Frame allows you to distribute "A" counters to monsters face up on the field, however you wish. The great thing about this effect is that it specifically says distribute. Meaning you can bypass non-targeting effects, which is a pretty awesome deal.   From there you can special summon Alien monsters from your GY up to the number of monster's your opponent controls with "A" counters. Bring out another Alien from your grave, to then Link Summon Cosmic Slicer Zer'oll. When he is out on the field, monsters with "A" counters are switched to defense position and cannot change their position (so long as there are counters on them) also they can no longer activate their effects. That's not all, Zer'oll also gives us the ability to add a card that can place "A" counters. From here you can pull any number of cards that add "A" counters, but this strategy will revolve around adding Alien Kid to your hand. Then, using Zer'oll's effect, remove 2 "A" counters from anywhere on the field to Normal Summon the Kid. Once Alien Kid is summoned, any monster your opponent special summons will have an "A" counter placed on them. Effectively preventing your opponent from activating effects or declaring an attack.   I have included a small Reptilianne engine for extenders as well as their Synchro Reptilianne Melusine. Her effect can activate every chain which means she can make all of your opponent's monsters attack 0. As I said... Welcome to Area 51, we come in peace....

It's a good thing we saw that flashback of Jaden drawing these cards as a child, because that explains why they have as many issues as they do. When playing a Neos deck, be prepared to activate Neos Fusion, having 7 options to choose from, then defaulting to 2 of them. Rainbow Neos is an incredibly versatile card to help even the playing field with your opponent. You'll want to go into him if your opponent has a field of monsters that you're not gonna be able to deal with, or a lot of backrow. If neither are the case, shuffling back their GY is costless and never hurts. Neos Kluger can swing for massive amounts of damage and deal a lot of burn. If you equip Kluger with Favorite HERO, you'll have a 6000 ATK beat-stick that burns your opponent for large amounts of damage. Since his burn effect is not OPT, you can use the second attack with Favorite HERO to hit in a second time to close the game. Favorite HERO is also the reason why we run a single copy of Neo Space. Sadly the other Neos Fusions aren't in the same league.  Starting with the two-piece fusions, Air Neos used to be the biggest beat-stick, but is more often than not outclassed by Kluger. Dark Neos can negate monster effects, but hits the field after most of the ones you'd want to negate are taken care of. Grand Neos spins a monster back, but so does Rainbow Neos. Aqua Neos is probably the best of these with his hand ripping effect, but is held back by it being random. Brave Neos searches for either Miracle Contact or Neos Fusion when he destroys a monster, which is a decent effect but is too slow. The triple/quad contact fusions are pretty great, but are a pain to summon. Cosmo Neos drains all your resources, but if you have lethal it ensures that nothing will stop you. Nebula Neos gives you some much needed draw power and negation. Storm Neos clears the backrow... (so does Rainbow Neos lol). All of these cards clear the field when they go home to visit grandma during the end phase.  This is usually not helpful during your end phase, and while it can be good during your opponents end phase with Neos Fusion's GY effect, you have to think about what you are possibly gonna do during your next turn after losing everything. Just pray you don't draw into any of the Neo Spacian's you shuffled back. Fusion Dispatch summons any of your Neo Spacians/Neos/Yubel from the Deck and helps a lot for contact fusing the larger monsters. NEXT is potentially a great card, but Neo Spacians and Neos rarely hang out in the GY. Miracle Contact keeps this deck somewhat playable. I wish Convert Contact didn't have the "control no monsters" restriction, but is otherwise your only draw power. Forbidden Droplet/Triple Tactics Talent/Pankratops are good for going 2nd (BTW good luck if you have to go first, you're gonna need it). Don't think too hard about the Link monsters. Verte Anaconda is basically the only one that matters. I honestly couldn't think of what else to put. Feel free to add in Neos Wiseman if you really want to float into him with Kluger, personally I didn't bother considering the massive amount of bricks Neos has to put up with already. While you're at it, go ahead and swap out the spare Grand Mole's, Dark Panther's, and link monsters for a copy of Flare Scarab, Glow Moss, and their fusions you absolute madman. Let me know what you think! This is by no means a definitive deck list.

deck_excerpt: A mediocre Marincess deck accompanied by a video where I show some of the deck's combos
deck_description: Combo guide Marincess is a midrange deck that can accrue tons of advantage off of one card, which even in worst case scenarios like drawing Pascalus and nothing else will still net you an interruption in Wave and a ridiculous amount of followup after getting its board broken.   A big issue the deck has is that, just like its fellow animal-based Cyberse-type control deck with huge amounts of recursion coming from the main cast in the VRAINS anime, Salamangreat, it dies really hard to Nibiru. To alleviate this weakness, where others see fit to play Crossout, which does go well into the deck, since it can fit a whole bunch of handtraps, I preferred to go with the option that probably won't cost me well over a hundred dollars and use a lot of WATER level 4 extenders to go into Bahamut Shark (who doesn't just represent an omninegate, but is also a free water body) by the 4th summon, with the added bonus of being decent at playing through interruptions other than handtraps when going second and helping you end on some of the strongest disruptive rank 4s in the game, like Kragen, Abyss Dweller or Toadally Awesome. Access to Stealth Kragen, particularly, can put this deck over the top, since it's sort of a boneless Destroyer Phoenix Enforcer, having a quick, non-targetting pop every turn and being able to float into itself while getting your resources back through Kragen Spawn, which you can attach Toad to from the GY. Foolish Burial Goods lets you send Ice Barrier to grab either one of your best extenders, Abyss Shark, or Gameciel to break boards (you can bounce Gameciel with Argonaut btw, it's really funny when it happens). Additionally, you can sometimes also send Fury of Kairyu-Shin to dodge stuff like DPE, or a Marincess backrow to add back with Rock/Anemone, which usually only comes up after you eat an Ash on Sea Angel.   Some rationalizations for changes I've made over other marincess builds and the previous versions of this deck: Mandarin isn't here because I've tried to lab plenty of combos using her, but I've only found that she helps you with making Argonaut unaffected through the field in some pretty specific hands and she isn't a very good card to draw. The setup she requires means she's pretty bad for extending after your combo gets interrupted too. Sleepy Maiden being level 5 and therefore not normal summonable or able to go into the link-1s or the Xyzs makes her kind of bad and testing the deck in real games has led me to believe the combos where you send her with Tang and use her effect to equip Anemone to Argonaut without needing the field aren't optimal most of the time, so I dropped her. I run 3 Pascalus because she helps a lot with making rank 4s while doing the Marincess stuff and a lot of people just shotgun imperm/veiler on her, which rarely does much of anything. She also gets you back Wave, Dive or Ocean, if it got destroyed, back to your hand turn 3 to go for the kill which is pretty good. I don't run Accesscode because almost every one of your really good cards locks you into water monsters and Argonaut ends up accomplishing pretty much the exact same thing while being easier to make, but I don't think it's necessarily wrong to run it if you can find space in your extra for it and Transcode.

deck_excerpt: Depending on your opening hand, you have three different ways that this deck can play out. Either Mayakashi, Shiranui, or Zombie World.
deck_description: Depending on your opening hand, you have three different ways that this deck can play out. This makes the deck varied in its plays and versatile in its response to threats. But in return for this, the deck is less consistent in getting any of its three strategies started. The ideal hand is one in which you can do your whole Mayakashi Synchro climb and send Necroworld Banshee to the grave with Yuki-Musume to activate Zombie World. This sets up your graveyard for future plays and forces your opponent to work around Zombie World. In the case that you do not open with a way to do your Synchro climb, the other starting cards you are looking for are Shiranui Squire, Shiranui Solitaire, Uni-Zombie, or Jack-o-Bolan. Shiranui Squire is an immediate Synchro Summon into Squiresaga which allows you to then banish Squire to fix your hand and fill your graveyard. Shiranui Solitaire allows you to go into a large number of cards depending on what else you have in hand. You can get out Dakki if you have Yuki-Musume in hand and continue with Mayakashi plays, or you can get out Uni-Zombie and set up for future turns. Uni-Zombie allows you to fill your graveyard with cards that can help accelerate your future plays and turns. And then Jack-o-Bolan is a fun card that can get a key card into your graveyard and allows you to interact with your opponent on their turn. The Zombie World and Rivalry of Warlords is always a fun lock to put up and is the only reason this deck can go up against meta decks. Swallow Slash is a better Icarus attack that can get rid of three things if you banish Shiranui Spiritmaster with its effect. And as a finisher, you have Sunsaga which resets the board and refills your Extra Deck. The easiest way to get out Sunsaga is with Balerdroch and Spectralsword, and can be done with both cards on the field, or with both cards in the graveyard. Overall, this is a very fun Zombie Deck that allows you to grind pretty hard once you get all the pieces in place, but loses if your starter gets negated or if your Graveyard gets banished to death.

deck_excerpt: Small world help..... more than you think
deck_description: So.... Small World came out and is a thing, right?     One of the biggest issues I've had with the deck over the past few months are those hands where you open unplayable. I've tried just about everything to help minimize those hands, but nothing really helped without losing just about every hand trap spot. Even then, I still bricked more often than I would like.     But small world is a thing now! This means that any machine or veiler in hand can turn into a dozer, metalcruncher, fortress, or bullet train (or anything other than harvester), and as and bell can turn into bullet train or harvester. All while naturally adding to the hand trap/interruption line up for the deck.     Try it out..... you may be pleasently surprised!

Main purpose of the deck is to put out fusions really fast like that of a shark XYZ deck, it uses cards from each archtype that uses the Fallen of Albaz as the main center piece of the decks, so swordsoul, despia, springans, tri-brigade, and dogmatika. This is a prerelease deck so it is subject to change, but with the field spell, fusion spell and main monster Albaz, it can allow you to put out fusion monsters rather quickly and pull cards from the deck in order to get a fusion so long as the deck is prepaired to do so. this is a basic template, so cards can be changed out to meet user needs.

deck_excerpt: An explosive meta deck that can play through almost anything given the right pilot
deck_description: This deck strategy is to either make an unbreakable board with either scythe+PE or fog blades+requiem. This deck's advantage is playing through handtraps(except D-shifter). This deck is also very good at going second with board breakers like breaksword, unicorn, and arc-rebellion. This decklist brought me first at a 45 man back to duel tourney which consisted of tri-brigade, drytron, ect. I feel as if this deck will be meta going into this format and is a deck with a kick. This list could be altered to fit more extenders or more handtraps depending on how you would like to play.

Monster Core (18 Monsters + 3 Hand-traps):     3x Swordsoul of Mo Ye: Main 1 Card Combo - for Level 8 Synchros +draw 1  3x Swordsoul Strategist Longyuan: Main 1 Card Combo - for getting to Level 10 Synchros +1,200LP Burn  3x Swordsoul of Taia: Main 1 Card Combo - for Level 8 Synchros +Foolish Burial  3x Incredible Ecclesia, the Virtuous: Potential Free Summon going 2nd to get to Mo Ye, or Taia  3x Tenyi Spirit - Ashuna: Another Free Summon, AND a Searcher for Tenyis  2x Tenyi Spirit - Vishuda: Compulsory Evacuation  2x Tenyi Spirit - Adhara: Free Summon, Recursion for longer duels. A Level 1 Tuner for Odd Level Synchros  3x Dimension Shifter: Chengyin Buffer, almost impossible to play around Handtrap (use during OPP's Draw Phase to dodge Gamma and Triple Tac)     Spells/Traps (17 Spells, 2 Traps):     3x Swordsoul Emergence: NAH, THIS IS THE HOLY SWORD "EXCALIBUR."  1-2x Swordsoul Sacred Summit: You only need one since it's mostly an OTK/Floodgate Deck, You may want to look into 2 or more for doubles tho.  3x Vessel for the Dragon Cycle: Triple ROTA/FOOLISH BURIAL. Say "No Mas." You get the ROTA effect when you link into Tenyi Shaman.  3x Pot of Desires: I think Prosperity is Preferred.. But this deck already $$$, this is good too tho because you get tons of recursion and buffs.  1x Called By the Grave: Hand-Traps? Watertho0o0ose.  3x Dark Ruler No More: OCG MUST, for us tho, idunno bro.  2-3x Triple Tac: Probably best card in our Group RN. You can swap them out for other stuff tho.  2x: Swordsoul Blackout: Double Pop, Also level 4 Tuner Token. If you pop Chengyin, you can use his effect to protect and still double pop.  0x Swordsoul Assessment: I don't really think you need this, it's an honest. I'd Probably only use it if you have a hard time outing Dragoon.     Extra Deck:     2x Swordsoul Grandmaster - Chixiao: Good for Banish Fueling, Imperm/Veiler Disruption Effect  1x Swordsoul Supreme Sovereign - Chengying: Boss Monster, 100 atk/def per banished, Banish effect, Hard to remove  2x Baxia, Brightness of the Yang Zing: Non-Destruction Removal, GY Recursion  1x Baronne de Fleur: Yeah. This Card's Busted. 'Nuff Said.  1x Cyber Slash Harpie Lady: OCG likes to run it for spells that have prerequisite Monsters (Flex Pick)  1x Chaofeng, Phantom of the Yang Zing: Light/Dark Protection from Hand-Traps  1x Virtual World Kyubi - Shenshen: Macro Cosmos (Monster Vers.)  1x Crimson Blader: Really good against our Meta, Prevents Lvl 5+ from being summoned. UCT? Virtual World? Dragoon? Eldich? Cyber Who?  1x Draco Berserker of the Tenyi: Non-Targeting Banish (DRAGOON?), Also Fat Beat-stick, probably stronger than Sovereign Chengyin.  1x Yazi, Evil of the Yang Zing: Extender. Disruption, I think every card in this deck is somehow a disruption tho.  1x Adamancipator Risen - Dragite: This card is so good, 5 Card deck peek, and Omni-Negate if you summoned using Mo Ye.  1-2x Monk of the Tenyi: Extender for any Tenyi monster, Because their effects can be used in HAND OR GRAVE ("O3O").     Side Deck:     1x Archnemeses Protos: 20$ Target Attribute Dark Hole + Floodgate. It's good, but can you afford it? $_$  3x Nibiru, the Primal Being: Always Good.  1x Dinowrestler Pankratops: Highly Rec in this deck, Even used in the OCG here.  3x Fantastical Dragon Phantazmay: Vs Link Decks, Sky Striker, Phantom Knights, Six Sam (1st Ogre/Nib, 2nd Droll Better tho), Arcana Knight, Sometimes CD.  3x Artifact Lancea: Good against Most decks, PK, Dinos, Eldlich.  1x Droll & Lock Bird: Guess not too popular in OCG  2x Twin Twisters/Cosmic Cyclone: Very Popular in OCG  1x Gadarla, the Mystery Dust Kaiju: For the Unexpected.     Alternative Extra Deck cards:     1x Swordsoul Catastrophe - Qixing Longyuan: Not out yet BUT BROKEN, HAS ALL OF THE ABOVE SS EFFECTS!!  1x Beelzeus of the Diabolic Dragons: Uhmmm, you actually can't summon it with any of the cards I mentioned.. But it's cool.  1x Beelze of the Diabolic Dragons: Lil' Bro of Beelzeus, But I still don't know how you get them out, OCG uses them often, I think you use Synchron Resonator?  1-2x Colossal Fighter: Versus Warrior Decks, This guy is a Beast. (Phantom Knights, Infernobles, HEROES, Six Samurai ( ͡° ͜ʖ ͡°) Poggers.)  1x Black Rose Dragon: OCG Favorite, But not as in Duos. Flex it if you want :^)  1x Geomathmech Final Sigma: This Card is unbeatable!! (Except by Cyber Dragon Chimeratechs)

deck_excerpt: Wipe your opponent's board with the supreme power of Arcanite Magician!
deck_description:
The ultimate goal is to get out Arcanite Magician from your Extra Deck to start popping things off your opponent's field. Once Synchro Summoned, he starts out with a total of 2400 ATK and two Spell Counters which will allow him to destroy two cards on your opponent's side of the field right off the bat. It's an unlimited trigger effect so you activate it any time during your turn to destroy as many cards equal to the amount of Spell Counters you have on him (or on the Magical Citadel of Endymion Field Spell). Here is the main combo which can be done on your very first turn simply by having Assault Sentinel:
  1. Normal summon Assault Sentinel and use its effect to tribute itself to special summon Psi-Reflector from your deck.
  2. Once Psi-Reflector is special summoned, you can use its effect to grab the Assault Mode trap card from your deck to your hand.
  3. Activate Psi-Reflector's second effect to reveal Assault Mode in your hand, special summon Assault Sentinel from your graveyard, and raise it's Level by 2 to make it Level 6 (because Arcanite Magician is Level 7).
  4. Activate Assault Sentinel's second effect to reveal Arcanite Magician from your Extra Deck to turn Assault Sentinel into a Spellcaster type.
  5. Now that Assault Sentinel has converted into a Spellcaster-type monster, this will allow you to ultimately Synchro Summon Arcanite Magician from your Extra Deck by tributing Psi-Reflector and Assault Sentinel.
  6. With Assault Mode still in your hand, you can simply set it and activate it during your opponent's turn to tribute Arcanite Magician and special summon Arcanite Magician/Assault Mode, which you will most likely do if you've already used up the two Spell Counters to destroy things, leaving him vulnerable at 400 ATK. You can also wait until your opponent targets Arcanite Magician with a Spell / Trap or during battle before activating Assault Mode.
If you happen to start off with Psi-Reflector in your hand, or is the only card you manage to have on-hand, you can still do the same exact combo except you'd have to discard Assault Beast instead. This will allow you to use Psi-Reflector's second effect to special summon Assault Beast from the graveyard in which they can both be used to special summon Assault Beast Ally of Justice Catastor from the Extra Deck. You can also use Foolish Burial to get Assault Sentinel into the Graveyard if you only have Psi-Reflector in-hand which will still allow you to get Arcanite Magician out. If you're getting overwhelmed by monsters and / or really need to get rid of a specific monster, you can easily Synchro Summon into Black Rose Dragon with Psi-Reflector and any Assault Mode monster (by raising the Levels of Assault Sentinel or Assault Beast by 3 Levels) if necessary. Emergency Teleport just acts as a fourth Psi-Reflector in the deck. I only run one since you only need one Psi-Reflector out to get things going. But you can feel free to run multiples if you'd like. One for One is basically the fifth Psi-Reflector, as it's the only monster this card can be used with. You really want to try to get a Psi-Reflector in your hand as soon as possible. Instant Fusion is only there specifically to special summon Musician King from the Extra Deck, in which then he can be used to special summon Supreme Arcanite Magician or other Link Monsters depending on the situation. The Pendulum Monsters; Endymion, the Mighty Master of Magic, Magical Abductor, Magister of Endyimion, Mythical Beast Jackal King, and Mythical Beast Master Cerberus, are just support engines I decided to run with to build up tons of Spell Counters for Arcanite Magician. You can actually overpower your opponent quickly with just the Pendulum Monsters and Apprentice Magician alone if you can't manage to draw out Psi-Reflector in time. If you happen to pull out Arcanite Magician late-game, you'd have about twenty Spell Counters to go nuts with by then. I'm still constantly tweaking the deck and currently changing around the ratios of the Pendulum Monsters and Pendulum Monster selection but so far this is what's playing more smoothly than all my previous builds when I'd first started it. Feel free to throw out any recommendations as I've just gotten back into this game recently. I'm not really trying to go for a meta / tournament build as I just wanted to play something fun, but I'm still open to those suggestions anyway.

Playing Style

  "War Rock" focuses on an aggressive playstyle centered around spamming the boards with monsters, battling opponent's monsters, and giving boosts of ATK to its members until the end of the opponent's turn after successfully activating their effects, allowing them to build up surprisingly high ATK in a short space of time. This is facilitated by their Field Spell, "War Rock Mountain", which can search a "War Rock" monster on activation and Summon a "War Rock" monster from the hand at the start of the Battle Phase while also protecting a "War Rock" from being destroyed by battle. Alongside this, most members of the archetype includes an effect in order to Summon themselves or another "War Rock"/Warrior monster to the field under certain conditions; usually related to battling, destruction, or leaving the field by an opponent's card effect. The Level 4 monsters of the deck, Fortia, Gactos, and Wento, Special Summon a Level 5 or higher "War Rock" monster from hand or Deck when sent to the GY by an opponent's card effect. The Level 5+ monsters include being able to Normal Summon themselves without Tribute, such as Orpis and Mammud, Skyler's effect to Special Summon a Level 5 or lower members of the theme from the GY, and Bashileos's effect to Special Summon itself from hand or GY when an EARTH Warrior is destroyed by battle. The only member without a Special Summon effect is War Rock Meteoragon, which can be seen as the theme's de facto boss monster and what most cards want to Special Summon to the field.

deck_excerpt: its your standard omni-zombie deck, but using the mayakashi trap engine
deck_description: main deck three of's:  solitaire: 3 - this is your best normal summon, this can create a 1 card combo that leads to halqifibrax (uni-zombie, send mezuki revive solitaire, summon halqi) allowing you to continue your combo further.  uni-zombie: 3 - another very good normal summon, can discard cards you want in graveyard or can send them from the deck to the graveyard. also is a level variable tuner, allowing access to a lot of your syncro line-up (besides locust since thats something that can be summoned off of halqi if necessary unless you really want to syncro it)  small world: 3 - can be used to search the cards you need to combo, since most of your deck is zombies you can grab basically anything, if you really need a negate in your match up you can even search ash blossom.  zombie world: 3 - it allows us to get away with summoning non zombie monsters, along with triggering balerdochs revive and possibly flood-gating the opponent  mezuki: 3 - a really good combo extender, never a bad choice if you can send something to the graveyard, you can re-use this card with omega and gmg (ghost meets girl) as well  ash blossom: 3 - its ash blossom, what else do i need to say besides the fact its searchable with small world  the gmg main deck engine:  gmg: 3 - if your able to get up to a link three and have one of the 9 (effectivly) copies of this card you can lock your opponent out of special summoning, its second effect can allow you to re-use graveyard effects that require banish's as well. Overall, its really good.  return: 3 - its (effectivly) 3 extra copies of gmg, thats all that matters  traptrick: 3 - its also (effectivly) 3 extra copies of gmg, thats all that matters  main deck 2 of's:  glow-up bloom: 2 - this is a level 1 tuner and a way to spec summon balerdoch or jack-o bolan (mostly balerdoch). you can easily make a link 2 zombie with just this card by summoning linkuriboh off of it.  balerdoch: 2 - its a level 8 body that can summon itself from the graveyard to draw off of sucker, be recurred as material for a i:p play and is a negate.  jack-o bolan: 2 - can special summon itself from the hand and can set up the graveyard with the discard, if needed it can draw you cards off of sucker as well.  Danger package:  danger nessie: 2 - the same as all the other dangers, we play this as graveyard setup, draws and field presence that can be turned into zombies  danger jackalope: 1 - the same as all the other dangers, we play this as graveyard setup, draws and field presence that can be turned into zombies  danger tsuchinoko: 1 - the same as all the other dangers, we play this as graveyard setup, draws and field presence that can be turned into zombies  danger mothman: 1 - the same as all the other dangers, we play this as graveyard setup, draws and field presence that can be turned into zombies  main deck 1 of's:  terraforming: 1 - its another copy of zombie world  foolish: 1 - its graveyard setup  one for one: 1 - graveyard setup and a way to get glow up bloom  banshee: 1 - another, easier way to get zombie world  gozuki: 1 - the worst of the nomal summon package but still good, if needed, you can send it for its second effect allowing you to continue combo's.  extra deck:  yuki onna link 4: 2 - a decent end monster, you can use yuki-onna link 3 to trigger a negate, as well as i:p sending a card with a when sent to the gy effect  yuki onna link 3: 2 -can be summoned off of I:P to get a negate, other than that is mainly just a cheap way to trigger gmg  vamp sucker: 2 - can draw you extra cards during your turn, or let you draw during your opponents.  avendread: 1 - can send cards but is mainly just a battle focused zombie link  halqi: 1 - the key to your combo's, can summon glow up bloom from the deck leading to easy combo's leading to your boss monsters, can also be used to summon locust for a discard and (if you control a level 4) a baronne during your opponents turn.  I:P: 1 - can summon yuki onna link 3 from the extra deck for negate  linkuriboh: 1 - is a way to get glow up bloom from the field to the gy  desert locust: 1 - is there to be a possible summon off of halqi, causes your opponent to discard cards and can summon baronne  red-eyes zombie: 1 - is a battle syncro that can revive, is only really in here to end games if you can do it normally  omega: 1 - can take banished blooms and mezuki's and put them back in the gy, as well as taking a card from our opponent's hand.  barronne: 1 - is here to be summoned from locust, can negate, destroy and revive.  big eye: 1 - idk he's just here for if we have spare jack-o's and nessies, not really important but idk what else to add

deck_excerpt: A guide on how to play Plant Control in Trinity Format!
deck_description:
Why play plants? Pros:
  • Extremely versatile answers
  • Generates massive amounts of card advantage
  • Great stalling potential
  • Powerful game ending disruption cards
  • Strong Mid-Late Game.
Cons:
  • Difficult to pilot effectively
  • Weak to disruption
  • Sometimes bricky
  • Difficult to close games out with
  • Slow early game
  • long games (if you don't like that sort of thing)
Why are we playing these engine's? Rikka: Your main advantage engine comes from Rikka Petal, when activated it searches you any "Rikka" monster and during our opponent's End Phase it summons itself back. Our choice of main deck monsters are Snowdrop the Rikka Fairy which is our XYZ/Synchro enabler, Mudan the Rikka Fairy who searches Rikka Sheet to disrupt our opponents or Rikka Tranquility that lets us stall or setup and Extra Deck play, Primula the Rikka Fairy who is a free body and helps us make our Rank 4 and 6 and lastly Erica the Rikka Fairy who lets us beat over big boss monsters and can revive itself from grave. Next is the Extra Deck Rikka's, First is Rikka Queen Strenna which is how we recycle our Rikka S/T and when tributed can "rank-up" into the other 2 if needed, Then we have Kanzashi the Rikka Queen that protects our monsters by tributing a plant monster in hand or field if they would be destroyed and can also act as Monster Reborn when a card has been tributed, Lastly is Teardrop the Rikka Queen who is our main boss monster and 1 of our main disruption tools, her first effect lets us Tribute our opponents monsters at SS2 and the second effect booster her by 200atk every time a card(s) is tributed. Aroma: Aroma since November 2021 had one of its main build arounds Aromaseraphy Sweet Marjoram banned but the deck still has a strong toolbox and drident-like removal with Teardrop the Rikka Queen. To replace her we've opted to play Aroma Gardening, Dried winds and 1 extra copy of Blessed Winds. This should make the Aroma engine still powerful just less consistent than previous builds where the goal was to turbo Sweet as fast as possible. Predaplant: This give us more disruption with predaplanning, strong fusion boss monsters and access to Super Polymerization one of the strongest board breaking cards in the game. This engine really helps solidify our mid game and keep our opponent off of big boss monsters. Traps: Our trap line-up is simple, Disrupt as much as possible. The rest are pure advantage cards that further push our greedy mid-late game.   Openers Our deck isn't that dependent on getting a starter but knowing what your options are is important. Here are the most common openers for the deck. Petal into Mardel: Summon Rikka Petal and activate its effect to search Mudan the Rikka Fairy, summon Mudan by tributing Petal and Activate Mudan to search Either Rikka Sheet for disruption or Rikka Tranquility for value. This is our standard opener and what we will typically do against most decks. Jasmine/Mardel: Summon Mathematician in the Centre Column and send Dandylion to summon 2 Tokens, Link both Tokens into Aromaseraphy Jasmine and activate its effect tributing Mathematician to summon Mardel, Generaider Boss of Light and search either Petal to get the Rikka engine started or Rose Girl if your engine is already going. Set 4 Pass: This is probably the 2nd most common opener in this deck but not necessarily a brick, as long as we can continually disrupt the opponent they will eventually have the same ceiling for power that we currently do, which is exactly what we want because we have inevitability in that once we draw our engine cards we can easily start out advantaging our opponent and win from there.   Midgame   Midgame is tricky because its extremely dependent on what your opponent is doing and what you have access to but generally at this point you should be deciding how many turns you can realistically close the game out in and how you are going to accomplish it. Here are some things to look out for in the midgame. Abusing Blessed Winds: Blessed Winds is one of your key cards in the mid game. Making sure you are using each effect to its fullest potential is important. Keeping your engine's going with the first of effect is crucial to get into a winning position, shuffling back your Rikka cards ensures you have the fuel to keep grinding out your opponent. Dodging removal with the 2nd effect is probably the single most important thing to keep in mind at all times, remember we only have 1 Rikka Petal and no way to recover it, if it's banished we are suddenly cut off from one of our main engines. The 3rd effect is a great value tool that lets us keep a strong board presence and re-use strong effects like Aromage Marjoram or Aromaseraphy Jasmine. Predaplant's: Midgame is where predaplants start becoming more relevant, Predaplanning can keep our opponent off of XYZ's and Synchro's while Predaplant Sarraceniant and Predaplant Drosophyllum Hydra can act as unconventional removal. Predaplant Verte Anaconda also spikes in the midgame turning any 2 monsters into Super Polymerization which can be game winning on it's own. Establishing Bosses: In the midgame we really want to summon our boss monsters like Teardrop the Rikka Queen or Benghalancer the Resurgent. While summoning Benghalancer can be difficult it can easily be game winning in the right board state so always look for for opportunity's to summon it. The Advantage Trinity: This is the point in the game where your secondary advantage engines start kicking in, Card of Safe Return, Dark Factory Of More Production and Supply Squad, These cards give us immense card draw and let us draw into our powerful trap cards in order to keep disrupting our opponent. Making the most of our traps: Traps are our main way of controlling the pace of the game and defending ourselves from big pushes from the opponent, knowing when and how to use your traps is matchup dependent but there are some fundamental's you can apply to any matchup.
  • Always keep your opponent's summon limit in mind when choosing when to use your disruption.
  • Is the card worth removing? If the card is easily removed in battle refrain from using your removal too early and save it for a bigger threat.
  • Am I on a clock? A clock refers to the amount of turns your opponent can lethal you from, if you feel like your opponent is trying to race you down then you can be more loose with your removal cards.
  • How much has my opponent committed to a play? The more value you can get from each of your removal cards the better, shotguning your Ring of Destruction too early might leave you with less value than if you had waited.
  Late Game Ending the game: By this point we should have enough board presence to close the game out with our boss monsters, always keep cards like Super Team Buddy Force Unite! and Erica the Rikka Fairy in mind when trying to close out games. Don't get too greedy: Ensure your plays are all trying to close out the game, don't keep playing for value as you may get punished by a top-deck from your opponent.   Closing Thoughts   Plants are an extremely fun and rewarding deck to learn and has a ton of deckbuilding options beyond just this list. Its grind game potential and flexible toolbox make it great into any meta with the right tech-cards and solid fundamentals.

deck_excerpt: SHOW THEM THE POWER OF UTOPIA! This non-meta deck focuses on the past strategy of Clownblade, where you can spam XYZ Rank 4s. OTK is possible on any t
deck_description:
SHOW THEM THE POWER OF UTOPIA! This non-meta deck focuses on the past strategy of Clownblade, where you can spam XYZ Rank 4s. However, with the times' progressing signs, there are also options to fusion and link summon while going against Top Tier Meta. Personally, it got me either on or very near the top 100 leaderboards on a popular online simulator website for Yu-Gi-Oh! (For the latest Yu-Gi-Oh! game Master Duel: I went from bronze 5 to platinum 3 with this deck in less than a few days). So I know this deck packs a powerful punch if you know what you are doing on certain moves. I'm a firm believer that rogue non-meta decks can not only compete on their own but also thrive on destroying meta decks to keep your opponent guessing.
  • It would help if you preferred to go second because:
1.) Most effect monsters in this deck have the effect of "If your opponent controls a monster and you control no monsters, you can special summon this card." 2.) You can One-Turn-Kill (OTK) with the "Number 39: Utopia Double" strategy. Minimum: You get a boosted 10,000 ATK or higher "Number 39: Utopia") by attacking into an opponent's attack mode monster, if and only if the opponent's monster has 2000 attack points or less (10000 ATK utopia minus 2000 ATK monster equals 8000 damage). It means you won when your opponent had 8000 life points or less. Utopia has some support cards in this deck to give other power boosts, protection, and other fun shenanigans. You can power up Utopia and get different variants of him on the field.
  • The Clownblade Performage Engine includes cards such as "Performage Trick Clown," "Performage Damage Juggler," and "Performage Hat Tricker." The Clownblade engine alone provides Level 4 monsters to spam, block any battle damage from opponent attacks, and block any burn effect damage.
  • There are Utopia support cards.
  • All other cards are tech and staples.
  • Side deck punishes spamming or specific game mechanics.
  • Some cards are in the deck for fun (Such as using the Melodious cards).
1. ) For example, you can use the fusion spell card, "Ostinato," to special summon "Schuberta the Melodious Maestra." By the effect of "Ostinato," that monster gets destroyed by the End Phase. Then you special summon "Aria the Melodious Diva" and "Elegy the Melodious Diva" from your Deck. Above is a formidable defensive board lock where your Melodious monsters cannot be targeted and cannot be destroyed by battle or card effects. There are few options to beat this board lock move. Your opponent can send (without targeting) those cards to the graveyard or banish zone, not targeting with card effects, such as "Super Polymerization," tributing with the Kaiju monsters archetype, or negating all card effects on the field, such as "Skill Drain." "Ostinato" uses cards from deck or hand. You can send more fodder Melodious cards to the graveyard to make the entire deck more consistent to make other moves without using Melodious cards.
  • Another fun thing is to run "Neos Fusion" to disrupt the field. Rainbow Neos works very well with the Utopia OTK.
  • Some other cards are situational, such as field spells and other spells/traps. This deck composes of spellcasters, fairies, and warriors.
  • You can XYZ, link, fusion, and synchro summon.
  • You can XYZ summon "Number 59: Crooked Cook" (A monster whose monster effect states: While you control no other cards on the field, this card is unaffected by other cards' effects). Combine this XYZ monster with XYZ materials such as "Astral Kuriboh" or "Right-Hand Shark," you can make a monster who is unaffected by anything and cannot be destroyed by battle (The only outs for "Number 59: Crooked Cook" are Kaiju-like monsters, piercing damage-effect monsters, having your opponent attack your life points directly, or prevent its summon in the first place).
  • You can still run it for Master Rule 4 or Master Rule 5.
  • You can run it for Master Duel.
Remember, if you believe in the heart of the cards, and you need a deck that can fit almost all situations, you should try out the deck. It's fun and competitive!

Official Card Game (遊☆戯☆王オフィシャルカードゲーム, Yū-Gi-Ō Ofisharu Kādo Gēmu) in Asia, is a Japanese collectible card game developed and published by Konami. It is based on the fictional game of Duel Monsters created by manga artist Kazuki Takahashi, which is the main plot device during the majority of the manga franchise, Yu-Gi-Oh, and its various anime adaptations and spinoff series.  "Floowandereeze" is a combination of "wander" and "breeze", with an additional "Floo" added to the front to approximate the archetype's Japanese name (while also being reminiscent of the English word "flew"). How to Play Charmer

Start with only using 3 simple Key Cards which is the only best I ever come out with for the Full Charmer's combos. Just following the recommendation cards that are listed below. ___________________________________________ [Key Cards]: 3 Main Engine - Spirit Charmers - Performage Damage Juggler - Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame [Recommend] to Search/Use - Lyna the Light Charmer (Hand) & Awakening of the Possessed (Spell/Trap Zone) - Performage Trick Clown (Hand) - Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden (Spell/Trap Zone) = Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires (Hand) ___________________________________________ Once you finally set up your cards. You will proceed with the next step by activating “Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires” effect to send out “Lyna, the Light Charmer” from your hand to the GY. Then use "Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires" effect to become Earth Attribute that allowed you to Summon “Awakening of the Possessed - Nefariouser Archfiend'' card from either hand or Deck by sending both “Crowley, the Magistus of Grimoires” and “Performage Trick Clown” from the field to the GY, which make them to trigger of their effects by Chain Link 2 and bringing it back “Lyna, the Light Charmer” from the GY to the field along with “Performage Trick Clown” by it own effect. Now you have finally had a chance to Summon “Familiar-Possessed Lyna” from either hand or Deck by its own effect. After that use “Familiar-Possessed Lyna” effect to search out “Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous” from your Deck then add it to your hand which is the only best Spellcaster monster with 1500 DEF/Level 4/Light Attribute monster that can be able to search out by "Familiar-Possessed - Dharc" effect when it Summoned by it own effect. Reminder: Do not activate "Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous" effect during your turn when it Summoned to your field, it will disable you for summoning from the Exta Deck unless if you have too. (This is an Optional) You will soon basically understand the concept of which cards you might ever use during the set up once you finally figure out how the Charmer's strategy works. Do the rest which I already listed of all the cards that might be used for the final board set up at the below. ___________________________________________ [End Board] • Field: - Borreload Salvage Dragon - I:P Masquerena + {Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous = Selene, Queen of the Magicians} (Opponent's Turn) • Spell/Trap: - Awakening of the Possessed (face-up) - Possessed Partnerships (set) = Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous (Opponent's Turn) - Artemis, the Magistus Moon Maiden (Spell/Trap Zone)(Equipped by "Borreload Salvage Dragon" effect) • Hand: - 1 Draw (Your turn) - Extra Draw (During your Opponent's Turn) - Added: Dogmatika Fleurdelis, the Knighted (During your Opponent's Turn) ___________________________________________ Tips: You might not actually get them from the opening hand with exactly cards. So I prefer you to try something else with different cards in your hand if one of the Key Cards are missing. You should better rely on your additional cards in your hand that might help you to set up your cards. Keep it in your mind that "Spirit Charmers" is just an additional card to use Familiar-Possessed - Lyna's Effect to search out "Dogmatika Ecclesia, the Virtuous" from your deck to the hand. Since Lyna & Dharc familiar monsters haven’t been revealed yet in TCG. I came up with those ideas by adding “Black Dragon Collapserpent” and “White Dragon Wyverburster” from the Deck to gain more consistency. I didn't actually plan to add them on my Deck in the first place since I want to prove that this Deck can win without relying on any Limited cards.  I might actually replace the “Black Dragon Collapserpent” and “White Dragon Wyverburster” including the “Chaos Space” later once the Light and Dark familiar’s monster has been finally released in TCG. By replacing it with two copies of “Grand Spiritual Art - Ichirin” Field Spell card and one “Terraforming” Spell card. ___________________________________________ [Additional] for more Consistency You can use "Summoner Monk" as additional for "Zoroa, the Magistus of Flame" or any Level 4 monster from your Deck like "Rilliona, the Magistus of Verre" or any Performage monster depending what card you need. Requirement: 1 any Spell card, except "Spirit Charmers" card, if not, you can use it as well if you have too. I include “Summoner Monk” from my Deck Profile since It actually works very well for any Level 4 monster.

deck_excerpt: Despia/shaddoll is a powerful going second deck that is well suited in the upcoming meta. If you're tired of making the exact same soulsword or drytro
deck_description: Despia is an archetype of dark fairy and light fusion fiend monsters that focus on fusion summoning. The archetype was initially released in dawn of majesty but didn't see much competitive success. However recent support in Burst of Destiny and changes to the surrounding meta game make this deck poised to be a powerful threat in the upcoming season. While there are many variations that can be done on the archetype, such as combining it with darklords for potential big boards and aliester for better fusion targets, this variation of mine combines despia with a shaddoll and predaplant package for going second and breaking boards. Let me go through some of the key cards.  Aluber, the Jester of Despia: This card is your main normal summon. He can search out either the field spell that fusion summons, or either of the quick play spells that can be used for offense or recovery. He also has a GY effect when a fusion is destroyed but since his effects are once per turn, once that turn, it doesn't come up much.  Despian Tragedy: This card is low-key amazing. Because his search effect triggers on either banish or sent to the GY by card effect, he can trigger off being fusion summoned, banished for allure, or sent by the quick play spells. His GY effect to reset a branded spell is also extremally useful.  Dramaturge and Libitum: these 2 Level 8 monsters are in the deck for extension plays when used as fusion material. They can be quite useful to go into dingirsu when you need to remove a problematic card.  Despia, Theater of the Branded: The deck doesn't die without the field spell up but it is easily much stronger when it is up. Obviously it fusion summons but the more interesting effect is when your non-fusion fairy(despia monsters are fairys) leaves the field by card effect or battle, you get to summon back a fusion monster from the GY. This turns so useful against something like nibiiru or a board wipe, since chances are you had both a fusion and a despia on field so it will trigger.  Branded Opening: This card is really good. It locks you into fusion monsters after usage but it puts a body on board or in hand, its discard is not a cost so it will trigger both tragedy and any of the shaddolls, and while in the GY it can protect a fusion by card destruction. all around a good card.  Shaddoll package: The shaddoll choices can vary and while they are not necessarily garnets, you don't want to see too many in your hand without a despia in there too. The only shaddoll monster you can(or rather want to) make with the field spell is construct and unless you side in some nibiru or effect veiler, you will have to rely on either your fusion monsters or your opponents light monsters. But Shaddoll fusion is still and amazing card and triggers basically any effect you want it too. Schism can be a great way to close out games by making winda as well.  Predaplant package: this is honestly a cuttable part of the deck. The reason I included it is monstly just cause its another way to make fusions, it is another super poly target, and its an allure banish at worst. If I can find something more powerful and consistent I will gladly swap it out.  EXTRA DECK:  Masquerade the Blazing Dragon: This is one of the new cards and frankly its amazing. Against heavy combo decks, even just one of these on the field means your opponent has just 13 card activations before they need to deal with it. which may sound like a lot but you would be surprised how many card activations it takes before a deck can get a pop or negation live. And since you're going second, this is both a super poly target and if you can't beat your opponent, you can still lower their life enough that they might have only 2, 1, or even 0 card activations left. Also its level 8 so another material for Dingirsu.  Despian Quarteris: This card is for cleaning up boards that don't have a dragoon or Phoenix enforce on them(that's what super poly is for), and floats into jester, which if the field spell is up will float into despian. A nice card all around.  Despian Proskenion: While a despia monster, a light, and a dark monster sound like a lot of material for a fusion, I can think of 2 decks whose end boards tend to have on them a light and dark( looking at you soulsword and drytron). Honestly, nothing feels better than summoning a jester, activating super poly to send away someone's herald of ultimentness and dragoon, then bring back their dragoon with Proskenions effect and win that way.     GENERAL GAMEPLAN: Your typical game plan is to blind second. Let your opponent set up and use bait cards like Opening and allure to bait interaction before blowing them away with your power cards of shaddoll fusion and super poly. If your opponent goes first, thats generally fine as masqurade or Quarteris can generally keep you alive with their floating and recusion, or if you open decent end on a winda. As noted earlier, Drytron and soulsword can get regularly hosed by this decks power cards, so your side deck should consist of counters to backrow heavy decks(which your only counter here is dragon and dingirsu) and specifically flunderezz(since that deck doesn't use the extra, isn't weak to superpoly, and doesnt special summon)

deck_description: Super Quantum Red Layer - This card is good for starting link plays since you can summon it and then any other of your monsters for an Isolde. It can bring a copy of itself from the GY to the hand, so it's good at combo-ing with Astolfo.  Sublimation Knight - Sublimation Knight is one of the best cards in this deck, since when it's summoned, it can let you bring out a free Isolde thanks to good synergy with Squeaknight. If it isn't in your starting hand, you can use Isolde's second effect to discard 3 Equips from the deck to summon out Sublimation Knight and continue your link plays.  Squeaknight - Squeaknight is almost solely here to combo with Sublimation Knight, but it also lets you bring out some syncrho monsters if you ever want to.  Infernoble Knight Renaud - Renaud is an amazing card, being a free special summon in almost any hand an can also return an equip spell from the GY, which is situationally useful.  Infernoble Knight Astolfo - Astolfo combos well with Isolde and Red Layer, being able to use the card they add to summon itself. It is also a combo piece with DDR, being a neat tech combo.  Boost Warrior - Boost Warrior is something you can use your normal summon on, or you can summon it if you have a special summoned Squeaknight on your field.  Fire Flint Lady - This card is a free special summon as long as you have any fire warrior on the field, which is easy for this deck. It can also be used to bring out Red Layer or Sublimation for extending Synchro plays.

deck_excerpt: If you thought that there was a better deck, I would say yes, but take this one into consideration too.
deck_description: This deck may not be flashy, but it gets the job done. You play way too many ways to send monsters to the GY (Hilariously, I don't actually play Foolish Burial), Snake Rain being the best starter in the deck. Snake Rain gets your combos going: Pitch any card, send Nunu, Nauya, Zohah, and a Keurse. Special summon nunu since you have no monsters, tribute it to Keurse, then summon Nauya. Nauya searches for your Lily, which you use to send you Aleirtt. Normal summon Zohah after you put it into your hand by dumping a card using his effect, and XYZ Nauya and it off for rikka queen. This is what I love about the deck: Rikka is your 5th summon, and since Nibiru tributes, you will still get the negate. Activate Aleirtt's effect to get rid of Rikka (If you haven't been Nibirued) and then use Queen's effect to summon your negate. If you are going first, take Keurse and Aleirtt, to XYZ summon for either Number 38 or 97. 97 will still get you into your Harbinger, but it is an extra body on the field. If you are going second, take the above combo, but do not go into harbinger, go into Draglubion who then will summon an 18K attack Numeron Dragon. Sadly this combo is pretty fragile, one Ash CAN and WILL make you probably lose the game, but if it is Ashed, go with this combo if you have it: Nunu Combo: Pitch Nunu to send Zohah, Dump a card to add Zohah to hand. Special Summon Nunu, Normal summon Zohah to XYZ into you King Of The Feral Imps. King searches for Nauya, then Nauya pitches for Keurse. Tribute your King Of The Feral Imps for Keurse, and summon Nauya. Nauya searches for your Lily, and Lily sends Aleirtt. Then it just becomes your basic snake rain combo at this point. There are other combos that this deck can do, with the reptilianne cards, but this is an Ogdoadic deck, after all   Other cards you may consider: Borreload Savage Dragon. In testing this card, it does get me out of rough spots, I would probably replace your Ahashima for this. Borreload or Borrelsword are also good cards. Also replace Ahashima with these. I Fell that's all I can really say about this deck. It's incredibly easy to get into and learn.

Spell Chronicle Combo:
